external_knowledge:
- 'Top-grossing movies' are those with the highest revenue within their respective genres.;
- 'Genre' refers to the category of the movie, such as action, drama, or comedy.;
- 'Production company revenue' is the annual revenue of the company that produced the movie.

- Top 10 highest-revenue and top 10 highest-budget movies are considered;
- 'Lucrative' refers to movies with high revenue;
- 'Costly' refers to movies with high budget.

- 'Animated treasures' refers to movies in the 'Animation' genre;
- 'Born between the dawn of the 1980s and the twilight of the 2020s' refers to movies released between 1980 and 2020;
- 'Golden touch' refers to production companies with an annual revenue greater than $100 million;
- 'Magical mark of $500 million' refers to the average revenue of the movies produced by the company being greater than $500 million.

- "money-making films" refers to movies with high revenue;
- "shining stars in the cinematic sky" is a metaphor for the top 10 highest-revenue movies;
- "backed by production companies with a thriving annual revenue" means the production companies have a positive annual revenue.

- "average revenue for its genre" refers to the mean revenue of all movies within the same genre;
- "genre" refers to a category of film, such as action, drama, or comedy;
- "production company" is the entity responsible for producing the movie.

sql:
SELECT MIN(release_date)
FROM movies
WHERE revenue > (SELECT AVG(revenue) FROM movies);

